BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
We have to substitute [`-3`] in for [`x`] and simplify each side:

[```\newcommand{\highlight}[1]{\mathchoice{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\displaystyle #1$}}{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\textstyle #1$}}{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\scriptstyle #1$}}{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\scriptscriptstyle #1$}}}\newcommand{\substitute}[1]{{\color{blue}{{#1}}}}\newcommand{\confirm}[1]{\stackrel{\checkmark}{#1}}\newcommand{\wonder}[1]{\stackrel{\text{?}}{#1}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
x^2+x+1\amp=\frac{3x+2}{x+2}\\
(\substitute{-3})^2+(\substitute{-3})+1\amp\wonder{=}\frac{3(\substitute{-3})+2}{\substitute{-3}+2}\\
\highlight{9}-3+1\amp\wonder{=}\frac{\highlight{-9}+2}{\highlight{-1}}\\
\highlight{6}+1\amp\wonder{=}\frac{\highlight{-7}}{-1}\\
\highlight{7}\amp\confirm{=}\highlight{7}
\end{aligned}
```]

Since [`7=7`] is true, [`-3`] is indeed a solution to this equation.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

